Certainly! If you want to extract the portion of text that matches the pattern "Accl ID = [Letters, numbers, and underscore]" from an anchor tag string that looks like this:

```html
<a href = "">Accl ID = TEST_TEST_1Accl ID = XXX</a>
```

You would need to use a Regular Expression (regex) in JavaScript to match that pattern. Here is an example of how you could do that:

```javascript
function extractAcclId(inputString) {
    // Regex pattern to match "Accl ID = " followed by letters, numbers and underscores
    const regexPattern = /Accl ID = [\w]+/g;

    // Matches all instances of the pattern in the input string
    const matches = inputString.match(regexPattern);

    // The output will contain the matched parts joined by the separator if more than one match is found
    return matches ? matches.join('') : '';
}

// Input string with anchor tag
const input = '<a href = "">Accl ID = TEST_TEST_1Accl ID = XXX</a>';

// Extracting the desired output
const output = extractAcclId(input);

console.log(output); // Should print: "Accl ID = TEST_TEST_1Accl ID = XXX"
```

The `\w` in the regex stands for "word character", which typically represents `a-z`, `A-Z`, `0-9`, including the underscore `_`. The `+` sign signifies that one or more of the preceding token (in this case word characters) are matched.

Do note that this regex pattern will match all instances of "Accl ID = " followed by the defined characters until the next whitespace or non-word character. If the format of the input string changes, the regex will need to be adapted accordingly.

Certainly! If you want to match and extract a substring from the provided HTML-like string and the substring is always expected to start with "Accl ID =" and contain letters, numbers, and underscores, here's how you can do it in JavaScript using Regular Expressions:

```javascript
function extractMatchedSubstring(inputString) {
    // Define a regex pattern to extract the desired part. This pattern looks for 'Accl ID ='
    // followed by any combination of alphanumeric characters and underscores until it hits a 
    // non-matching character or the end of the string.
    const regexPattern = /Accl ID = [A-Za-z0-9_]+/g;

    // Use 'match' function to find all occurrences that match the pattern in the input string
    const matches = inputString.match(regexPattern);

    // If there are matches, concatenate them to form the output
    // Here, we assume that the 'Accl ID' segments are contiguous in the string.
    let output = '';
    if (matches) {
        output = matches.join('');
    }

    return output;
}

// Input HTML-like string
const input = '<a href = ""> Accl ID = TEST_TEST_1Accl ID = XXX</a>';

// Extract string using the above function
const output = extractMatchedSubstring(input);

console.log(output); // This will log: "Accl ID = TEST_TEST_1Accl ID = XXX"
```

In the regular expression used above:

- `\s*` matches any whitespace characters (spaces, tabs, etc.), and allows for none or multiple occurrences due to the asterisk `*`.
- `[A-Za-z0-9_]+` matches one or more (`+`) occurrences of alphanumeric characters (`A-Za-z0-9`) and underscores (`_`).

You can test this script in a JavaScript environment, such as a browser console or Node.js, and it should give you the expected output.
